 veteran soldiers from the Imperial Japanese Army (Japanese ''Devils shed light on a dark past'') CNN\n** [http://www.midnighteye.com/reviews/japdevil.shtml ''Japanese Devils''], Midnight Eye,\n* {{Cite video | people= The History Channel | date= 2000 | url= | title = Japanese War Crimes: Murder Under The Sun | medium = Video documentary (DVD & VHS) | location = | publisher= A & E Home Video}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Please alphabetize according to display title -->\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070609112646/http://home.pacbell.net/fbaldie/Battling_Bastards_of_Bataan.html Battling Bastards of Bataan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080113004217/http://www.sjwar.org/ \"Biochemical Warfare \u2013 Unit 731\". Alliance for Preserving the Truth of Sino-Japanese War.] No date.\n* [http://www.warbirdforum.com/cannibal.htm \"Cannibalism\". Dan Ford, \"Japan at War, 1931\u20131945\"] September 2007.\n* [http://www.centurychina.com/wiihist/confess/index.html \"Confessions of Japanese war criminals\".] No date.\n* [https://fas.org/nuke/guide/japan/bw/ \"History of Japan's biological weapons program\"] [[Federation of American Scientists]], 2000-04-16\n* [http://www.systemclub.co.kr/ Ji Man-Won's website (in Korean)] Various dates.\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/elsewhere/journalist/story/0,7792,1338296,00.html Justin McCurry, \"Japan's sins of the past\"] in ''[[The Guardian]]'', 2004-10-28\n* [https://www.archives.gov/iwg/ Nazi War Crimes and Japanese Imperial Government Records Interagency Working Group (IWG) ] U.S. [[National Archives and Records Administration]] (NARA). No date.\n* [http://www.skycitygallery.com/japan/japan.html \"The Other Holocaust\"] No date.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041009171355/http://www.kimsoft.com/2002/jp-rape.htm \"Rape of Queen MIN\"] 2002\n* [http://www.hawaii.edu/powerkills/SOD.CHAP3.HTM R.J. Rummel, \"Statistics Of Japanese Democide: Estimates, Calculations, And Sources\" ] [[University of Hawaii]], 2002\n* [http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2002/08/28/1030508070534.html Shane Green. \"The Asian Auschwitz of Unit 731\" ] in ''[[The Age]]'', 2002-08-29\n* [http://www.mofa.go.jp/announce/press/pm/murayama/9508.html \"Statement by Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama\"] 1995-08-15\n* {{Cite web |url=http://www.technologyartist.com/unit_731/ |title=Steven Butler, \"A half century of denial: the hidden truth about Japan's unit 731\" |access-date=October 31, 2004 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061119053825/http://www.technologyartist.com/unit_731/ |archive-date=November 19, 2006 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=mdy-all }} in ''[[US News & World Report]]'' 1995-07-31\n* [http://histclo.com/essay/war/ww2/pow/pow-jap.html Japanese Treatment of World War II POWs]\n\n{{JapanEmpireNavbox}}\n{{IJA special research units}}\n{{World War II}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Japanese War Crimes}}\n[[Category:Anti-Japanese sentiment in China]]\n[[Category:Anti-Japanese sentiment in Korea]]\n[[Category:Historical negationism]]\n[[Category:History of Asia]]\n[[Category:Imperial Japanese Army]]\n[[Category:Imperial Japanese Navy]]\n[[Category:Incidents of cannibalism]]\n[[Category:Japanese culture]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes| ]]\n[[Category:Military history of Japan]]\n[[Category:War crimes committed by country]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAttacks on hospital ships:crew", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_war_crimes"}
{"title_page": "Mike Levine (newspaper writer)", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup|reason=reads too much like an obituary rather than an encyclopedia article|date=March 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2012}}\n}}\n\n'''Mike Levine (newspaper writer)''' (May 2, 1952 in [[New York City, New York]] \u2013 January 14, 2007 in Monroe, New York) was an award-winning newspaper and magazine journalist, columnist, and editor, best known for his writing and leadership roles at the ''[[Times Herald-Record]]'' and [[ESPN]].\n\n==Career as a Journalist, Editor, and Author==\n\nLevine began his writing career as the editor of ''Heights-Inwood''. He began working at the ''Times-Herald Record'' in July 1980, and was assigned to cover stories in [[Sullivan County, New York]] for years. He became a regular columnist in 1983. His reporting was said to have a flair for sentimental human interest stories with an articulate and compassionate voice, mixed with wisdom, humor and old-fashioned journalistic muckraking.{{by whom|date=April 2012}} He worked his way up to Executive Editor in 1999, covering the Hudson Valley, Catskill, Ulster and Orange County regions. From 2001 to 2002, he was Senior Editor of ''ESPN The Magazine'' and from 2002, Executive Editor of the ''Times Herald-Record''.\n\n==Death==\n\nLevine died of a heart attack at home on January 14, 2007, and was survived by his wife (Ellen), four children, and a sister (Tedra).<ref>http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070115/NEWS/70115002</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nThe Mike Levine Journalism Education Fund was founded after his death. Beginning in 2010, the fund sponsors an annual training for aspiring writers at The Mike Levine Workshop in Livingston Manor, New York. The workshop is led with prominent writers serving as volunteers.<ref>http://www.mikelevineworkshop.org/index.php?section=3</ref> In addition, an annual Mike Levine column 'Read-a-Thon' is held annually to raise money for the Education Fund.<ref>http://thecatskillchronicle.com/2010/01/08/third-annual-mike-levine-column-read-a-thon/</ref><ref>{{YouTube|3rh-wyljTQM}}</ref> Levine is the first writer in the history of the Times-Herald Record for whom every article he had ever written has made available by online archive. The article listing online is free with click on links, but at present the archive does require a subscription to the Record's online service for access.<ref>http://www.mikelevineworkshop.org/~mikelevi/index.php?section=13</ref> A clip of Mr. Levine addressing his community is on YouTube.<ref>{{YouTube|Uv5YFq8dLlk}}</ref>\n\n==Free Writings Online==\n\n* The Miracle, April 1999 column Part I by Mike Levine <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutbacf.org/the-miracle/the-miracle-part-1/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020140308/http://www.aboutbacf.org/the-miracle/the-miracle-part-1/ |archivedate=2011-10-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tonionny.com/be-thankful-for-your-family-a-heart-breaking-true-story |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120724060935/http://www.tonionny.com/be-thankful-for-your-family-a-heart-breaking-true-story |archivedate=2012-07-24 }}</ref>\n* The Miracle, April 1999 column Part II by Mike Levine <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutbacf.org/the-miracle/the-miracle-part-2 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020140313/http://www.aboutbacf.org/the-miracle/the-miracle-part-2/ |archivedate=2011-10-20 }}</ref>\n* The Miracle, April 1999 column Part III by Mike Levine <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutbacf.org/the-miracle/the-miracle-part-3 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020140452/http://www.aboutbacf.org/the-miracle/the-miracle-part-3/ |archivedate=2011-10-20 }}</ref>\n* First Day of School: Moments To Treasure <ref>{{cite web |url=http://parents.msmilgrimsmathclass.com/thrlevine.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120712235839/http://parents.msmilgrimsmathclass.com/thrlevine.html |archivedate=2012-07-12 }}</ref><ref>http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070905/NEWS/709050337</ref>\n* Thanksgiving Bless In Memory of Debbie <ref>http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070115/NEWS/70115892/-1/NEWS271993</ref><ref>http://www.poconorecord.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20111124/NEWS/111240306/-1/rss01</ref>\n* Somewhere in the Issues is the Truth <ref>http://www.bishop-accountability.org/news3/2007_01_15_Levine_SomewhereIn_Juan_Bazalar_4.htm</ref>\n* MIke Levine's last column in the [[Times Herald-Record]] <ref>http://mikelevineworkshop.org/blog2/?p=532</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.th-record.com ''Times Herald-Record'' online]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levine, Mike}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup|reason=reads too much like an obituary rather than an encyclopedia article|date=March 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=March 2012}}\n}}\n\n'''Mike Levine (newspaper writer)''' (May 2, 1952 in [[New York City, New York]] \u2013 January 14, 2007 in Monroe, New York) was an award-winning newspaper and magazine journalist, columnist, and editor, best known for his writing and leadership roles at the ''[[Times Herald-Record]]'' and [[ESPN]].\n\n==Career as a Journalist, Editor, and Author==\n\nLevine began his writing career as the editor of ''Heights-Inwood''. He began working at the ''Times-Herald Record'' in July 1980, and was assigned to cover stories in [[Sullivan County, New York]] for years. He became a regular columnist in 1983. His reporting was said to have a flair for sentimental human interest stories with an articulate and compassionate voice, mixed with wisdom, humor and old-fashioned journalistic muckraking.{{by whom|date=April 2012}} He worked his way up to Executive Editor in 1999, covering the Hudson Valley, Catskill, Ulster and Orange County regions. From 2001 to 2002, he was Senior Editor of ''ESPN The Magazine'' and from 2002, Executive Editor of the ''Times Herald-Record''.\n\n==Death==\n\nLevine died of a heart attack at home on January 14, 2007, and was survived by his wife (Ellen), four children, and a sister (Tedra).<ref>http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070115/NEWS/70115002</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nThe Mike Levine Journalism Education Fund was founded after his death. Beginning in 2010, the fund sponsors an annual training for aspiring writers at The Mike Levine Workshop in Livingston Manor, New York. The workshop is led with prominent writers serving as volunteers.<ref>http://www.mikelevineworkshop.org/index.php?section=3</ref> In addition, an annual Mike Levine column 'Read-a-Thon' is held annually to raise money for the Education Fund.<ref>http://thecatskillchronicle.com/2010/01/08/third-annual-mike-levine-column-read-a-thon/</ref><ref>{{YouTube|3rh-wyljTQM}}</ref> Levine is the first writer in the history of the Times-Herald Record for whom every article he had ever written has made available by online archive. The article listing online is free with click on links, but at present the archive does require a subscription to the Record's online service for access.<ref>http://www.mikelevineworkshop.org/~mikelevi/index.php?section=13</ref> A clip of Mr. Levine addressing his community is on YouTube.<ref>{{YouTube|Uv5YFq8dLlk}}</ref>\n\n==Free Writings Online==\n\n* The Miracle, April 1999 column Part I by Mike Levine <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aboutbacf.org/the-miracle/the-miracle-part-1/ |title=Archived copy |accessd