umn in the [[Times Herald Record]] <ref>http://mikelevineworkshop.org/blog2/?p=532</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.th-record.com ''Times Herald-Record'' online]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levine, Mike}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:American newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n", "name_user": "Agathoclea", "label": "safe", "comment": "Redirect bypass fromTimes Herald RecordtoTimes Herald-Recordusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Levine_(newspaper_writer)"}
{"title_page": "White Fathers", "text_new": "{{redirect|Missionaries of Africa||Category:Christian missions in Africa}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| image = [[Image:Cardinal Lavigerie.jpg|frameless|centre|200px|]]\n| caption = [[Cardinal Lavigerie|Charles Martial Lavigerie]]\n| formation = {{start date and age|1868}}\n| type = Society of Apostolic Life of Pontifical Right (for Men)\n| headquarters = Via Aurelia, 269, 00165 Roma, Italy\n| leader_title = Superior General\n| leader_name = Fr. Stanley Lubungo, M. Afr.\n| native_name = P\u00e8res Blancs\n| name = Missionaries of Africa<br><small> White Fathers</small>\n| founding_location = [[Algiers]]\n| founder = [[Charles Lavigerie|Cardinal Charles Lavigerie]]\n| membership = 1,191 members (2019)\n| website = {{url|mafrome.org}}\n| abbreviation = M. Afr.\n}}The '''Missionaries of Africa''', commonly known as the '''[[White Fathers]]''' or the '''Society of the Missionaries of Africa''' ([[French language|French]]: ''P\u00e8res Blancs''; [[Post-nominal letters|post-nominals]]: '''M. Afr.''') are a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[society of apostolic life]]. Founded in 1868 by [[Archbishop]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Algiers|Algiers]] [[Charles Lavigerie|Cardinal Charles Lavigerie]], the society focuses on [[evangelism]] and [[education]], mostly in Africa. As of 2020, there were 1247 Missionnaires of Africa, of 36 Nationalities, working in 42 Countries, in 217 communities.<ref name=blanc/> \n\n==History==\n{{Refimprove|section|date=March 2020}}\n[[image:Maison-Carr\u00e9e P\u00e8res Blancs.jpg|thumb|right|The first convent in Maison-Carr\u00e9e.]] \nThe [[cholera]] epidemic 1867 left a large number of [[Algeria]]n orphans, and the education and Christian instruction of these children was the occasion of the founding of the society in Maison-Carr\u00e9e (now [[El-Harrach]]) near [[Algiers]]; but from its inception the founder had in mind the conversion of the Arabs and the peoples of Central Africa. Lavigerie instructed his missionaries to speak the language of the people, eat the same food, and wear the same clothing. They therefore, adopted the Arabian dress: the [[gandoura]], the Arab cloak and the [[Taqiyah (cap)|chechia]], with as a religious sign a rosary worn around the neck like necklace.<ref name=blanc>[http://peresblancs.org/histoi1a.htm Ceillier, Jean-Claude Ceillier. \"The origins and Presentation of Our Society\", ''Peres Blanc'']</ref> The nickname \"White Fathers\" derives from their garb.  \n\nA novitiate was established in 1868. Missionary posts were established in [[Kabylie]] and in the [[Sahara]]. In 1876 three missionaries on their way to [[Timbuktu]] were killed by desert nomads.<ref name=blanc/> In 1878 ten missionaries left [[Algiers]] to establish posts at Lakes [[Lake Victoria|Victoria]], [[Lake Malawi|Nyassa]] and [[Lake Tanganyika|Tanganyika]].<ref name=Forbes>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/15613d.htm Forbes, John. \"White Fathers.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 15. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 3 March 2020{{PD-notice}}</ref> In 1878, a caravan of several missionaries arrives at the port of [[Mombasa]], and after a three month trek reach [[Lake Victoria]]. \n\nIn 1880, at the request of the Holy See, the White Fathers established at Jerusalem a [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Greek Melchite]] seminary for the formation of clergy of that rite. In 1894 a mission in [[French Sudan]] (now [[Mali]]) was founded.<ref name=Forbes/>\n\n==Present day==\nThese now form the present Lakes [[Archdiocese]]s of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Kampala|Kampala]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Gitega|Gitega]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tabora|Tabora]], and the dioceses of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kigoma|Kigoma]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lilongwe|Lilongwe]], and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kalemie-Kirungu|Kalemie-Kirungu]]. \n\nThe society is composed of missionary priests and brothers. The members are bound by an oath engaging them to labour for the conversion of Africa according to the constitutions of their society. The missionaries are not, strictly speaking, a [[religious institute]], whether \"[[Catholic religious order|order]]\" or \"[[Congregation of Papal Right|congregation]]\". Instead, they are a [[society of apostolic life]]. They may retain their own property; but they may expend it in the society only at the direction of the superiors. \n\n==Aims==\nOne of the chief points in the rule is in regard to community life in the missions, each house being obliged to contain at least three members. At the head of the society is a General-Superior, elected every six years by the chapter. He resides in Rome at the Generalate house on Via Aurelia. Those desiring to become priests or brothers are admitted to the [[novitiate]] after their [[Philosophy|philosophical]] studies. After the novitiate they spent two years of missionary training on the field and four years of [[theology]]. This training can be slightly different for brother candidates. The theological studies  are spent in scholasticate presently located in Abidjan ([[Ivory Coast]]), Nairobi ([[Kenya]]), [[Merrivale, Devon|Merrivale (Devon)]], [[South Africa]] and [[Jerusalem]]. The society admits persons of all nationalities.\n\n==Dress and membership==\nThe habit of the missionaries resembles the white robes of the Algerian Arabs and consists of a [[cassock]] or [[gandoura]], and a [[Mantle (vesture)|mantle]] or [[burnous]]. A [[rosary]] and [[cross]] are worn around the neck in imitation of the [[mesbaha]] of the [[marabout]]s.\n\nThe society depends directly on the [[Congregation for the Evangelization of Peoples]]. The White Fathers succeeded in establishing small missions among the [[Kabyle people|Kabyle Berbers]], there being at present nine hundred and sixty-two Christians; but the regions bordering on the Great Lakes and Sudan show the best results. The number of [[wikt:neophyte|neophyte]]s in all the vicariates (as of June 1909) was 135,000; the number preparing for [[baptism]] 151,480. A test of four years is imposed on those desiring to be baptized. To religious instruction the missionaries add lessons in reading and writing, and teach also, in special classes, the tongue of the European nation governing the country, which was mostly French in these areas. The brothers train the young people for trades and agriculture. The number of boys in the schools (June, 1909) was 22,281.[[Image:Cypress Grove House.jpg|thumb|Cypress Grove House, home of the White Fathers in Ireland]]\n\nIn January 2006, the society numbered; 9 bishops, 1,498 priests, 156 brothers; 16 clerics with perpetual oath, and 5 associates. There were 354 students preparing to enter the society.\n\n==Leaders==\n\nUnder the leadership of Archbishop (later Cardinal) [[Charles Lavigerie|Charles-Martial Allemand-Lavigerie]], General Superiors were:<ref name=MafrGCatholic>{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Missionaries of Africa M. Afr.||}} |url=http://www.gcatholic.org/orders/030.htm\n |title=Missionaries of Africa M. Afr.|| |work=GCatholic|accessdate=2013-04-19}}</ref>\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n| 1874 || 1880|| Fr. Francisque Deguerry\n|-\n| 1880 || 1885|| Fr. [[Jean-Baptiste-Fr\u00e9zal Charbonnier]] (later Bishop)\n|-\n| 1885? || 1886|| Fr. [[L\u00e9once Bridoux]] (later Bishop)\n|-\n| 1886 || 1889|| Fr. Francisque Deguerry\n|-\n| 1889 || 1894||Bishop [[L\u00e9on Livinhac]] (later Archbishop)\n|}\n[[File:Mgr Lavigerie.jpg|thumb| Lavigerie memorial in [[Algiers]]]]\nLater Superiors General were:<ref name=MafrGCatholic/>\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n| 1894 || 1922.11.11|| Archbishop [[L\u00e9on Livinhac]]\n|-\n| 1922 || 1936|| Fr. [[Paul Voillard]]\n|-\n| 1936.04.22 || 1947.04.30|| Bishop [[Joseph-Marie Birraux]] \n|-\n| 1947.05.05 || 1957|| Bishop [[Louis-Marie-Joseph Durrieu]] \n|-\n| 1957 || 1967|| Fr. [[L\u00e9on Volker]] \n|-\n| 1967 || 1974|| Fr. [[Th\u00e9oz Van Asten]]\n|-\n| 1974 || 1980|| Fr. [[Jean-Marie Vasseur]] \n|-\n| 1980 || 1986|| Fr. [[Robert Marie Gay]] (later Bishop)\n|-\n| 1986 || 1992|| Fr. [[Etienne Renaud]]\n|-\n| 1992 || 1998|| Fr. [[Gothard Rosner]] \n|-\n| 1998 || 2004.06.02|| Fr. [[Fran\u00e7ois Richard, White Father|Fran\u00e7ois Richard]] \n|-\n| 2004.06.02 || 2010.05.31|| Fr. [[G\u00e9rard Chabanon]]\n|-\n| 2010.05.31 ||  || Fr. [[Richard Baawobr]] (became Bishop of Wa - Ghana earlier in 2016)\n|- \n| 2016.05.27 ||  || Fr. [[Stanley Lubungo]]\n|}\n\n==Zambia==\nThe White Fathers also created mission stations in what was then [[Northern Rhodesia]] (now [[Zambia]]), particularly in the [[Luwingu]] District.  \n\n'''The Catholic Church in Zambia and the Missionaries of Africa (The White Fathers)''' (from the General House of the Missionaries of Africa - White Fathers)\n\nThe first Catholic Missionaries in what is now called Zambia were the international Society of the Missionaries of Africa, popularly called 'The White Fathers\u2019 because of their white dress. They arrived from what is now called Tanzania in 1891, and established the first mission post called Mwambwe Mwela. They were hierarchically structured with Bishop Joseph Dupont firmly in charge , something that appealed to the Bemba overlords. One of the reasons that bloodshed was avoided was his reconciliation during one of their succession disputes. They settled down successfully in the North of what was then called Northern Rhodesia but did not follow those who migrated to the copper mines and the capital Lusaka during the 1930's. This practice was changed in 1965, after the Second Vatican Council, when a younger group of White Fathers responded to the national requirements of the apostolate. \nAround the beginning of the new millennium their missionary endeavour was taken over, almost entirely, by the local clergy.\n\n==See also==\n[[File:Maison g\u00e9n\u00e9ralice.jpg|thumb|right|General House in Rome]]\n* [[Catholic missions]]\n* [[Burkard Huwiler|Bishop Burkhard Huwiler]]\n* [[Joseph Dupont (bishop)|Bishop Joseph Dupont]]\n* [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church]]\n* [[Kungoni|Mua Mission, Malawi]]\n* [[Catholic youth sports associations of French Algeria]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{CathEncy|wstitle=White Fathers}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://mafrome.org/home/ International Website of the Missionaries of Africa]\n* [http://www.missionariesofafrica.org/ Missionaries of Africa UK]\n* [http://www.mafrwestafrica.net/ Missionaries of Africa in West Africa]\n\n[[Category:White Fathers| ]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1868]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Missionaries of Africa||Category:Christian missions in Africa}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| image = [[Image:Cardinal Lavigerie.jpg|frameless|centre|200px|]]\n| caption = [[Cardinal Lavigerie|Charles Martial Lavigerie]]\n| formation = {{start date and age|1868}}\n| type = Society of Apostolic Life of Pontifical Right (for Men)\n| headquarters = Via Aurelia, 269, 00165 Roma, Italy\n| leader_title = Superior General\n| leader_name = Fr. Stanley Lubungo, M. Afr.\n| native_name = P\u00e8res Blancs\n| name = Missionaries of Africa<br><small> White Fathers</small>\n| founding_location = [[Algiers]]\n| founder = [[Charles Lavigerie|Cardinal Charles Lavigerie]]\n| membership = 1,191 members (2019)\n| website = {{url|mafrome.org}}\n| abbreviation = M. Afr.\n}}The '''Missionaries of Africa''', commonly known as the '''White Fathers''' or the '''Society of the Missionaries of Africa''' ([[French language|French]]: ''P\u00e8res Blancs''; [[Post-nominal letters|post-nominals]]: '''M. Afr.''') are a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[society of apostolic life]]. Founded in 1868 by [[Archbishop]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Algiers|Algiers]] [[Charles Lavigerie|Cardinal Charles Lavigerie]], the society focuses on [[evangelism]] and [[education]], mostly in Africa. As of 2020, there were 1247 Missionnaires of Africa, of 36 Nationalities, working in 42 Countries, in 217 communities.<ref name=blanc/> \n\n==History==\n{{Refimprove|section|date=March 2020}}\n[[image:Maison-Carr\u00e9e P\u00e8res Blancs.jpg|thumb|right|The first convent in Maison-Carr\u00e9e.]] \nThe [[cholera]] epidemic 1867 left a large number of [[Algeria]]n orphans, and the education and Christian instruction of these children was the occasion of the founding of the society in Maison-Carr\u00e9e (now [[El-Harrach]]) near [[Algiers]]; but from its inception the founder had in mind the conversion of the Arabs and the peoples of Central Africa. Lavigerie instructed his missionaries to speak the language of the people, eat the same food, and wear the same clothing. They therefore, adopted the Arabian dress: the [[gandoura]], the Arab cloak and the [[Taqiyah (cap)|chechia]], with as a religious sign a rosary worn around the neck like necklace.<ref name=blanc>[http://peresblancs.org/histoi1a.htm Ceillier, Jean-Claude Ceillier. \"The origins and Presentation of Our Society\", ''Peres Blanc'']</ref> The nickname \"White Fathers\" derives from their garb.  \n\nA novitiate was established in 1868. Missionary posts were established in [[Kabylie]] and in the [[Sahara]]. In 1876 three missionaries on their way to [[Timbuktu]] were killed by desert nomads.<ref name=blanc/> In 1878 ten missionaries left [[Algiers]] to establish posts at Lakes [[Lake Victoria|Victoria]], [[Lake Malawi|Nyassa]] and [[Lake Tanganyika|Tanganyika]].<ref name=Forbes>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/15613d.htm Forbes, John. \"White Fathers.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 15. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 3 March 2020{{PD-notice}}</ref> In 1878, a caravan of several missionaries arrives at the port of [[Mombasa]], and after a three month trek reach [[Lake Victoria]]. \n\nIn 1880, at the request of the Holy See, the White Fathers established at Jerusalem a [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church|Greek Melchite]] seminary for the formation of clergy of that rite. In 1894 a mission in [[French Sudan]] (now [[Mali]]) was founded.<ref name=Forbes/>\n\n==Present day==\nThese now form the present Lakes [[Archdiocese]]s of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Kampala|Kampala]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Gitega|Gitega]], [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Tabora|Tabora]], and the dioceses of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kigoma|Kigoma]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lilongwe|Lilongwe]], and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kalemie-Kirungu|Kalemie-Kirungu]]. \n\nThe society is composed of missionary priests and brothers. The members are bound by an oath engaging them to labour for the conversion of Africa according to the constitutions of their society. The missionaries are not, strictly speaking, a [[religious institute]], whether \"[[Catholic religious order|order]]\" or \"[[Congregation of Papal Right|congregation]]\". Instead, they are a [[society of apostolic life]]. They may retain their own property; but they may expend it in the society only at the direction of the superiors. \n\n==Aims==\nOne of the chief points in the rule is in regard to community life in the missions, each house being obliged to contain at least three members. At the head of the society is a General-Superior, elected every six years by the chapter. He resides in Rome at the Generalate house on Via Aurelia. Those desiring to become priests or brothers are admitted to the [[novitiate]] after their [[Philosophy|philosophical]] studies. After the novitiate they spent two years of missionary training on the field and four years of [[theology]]. This training can be slightly different for brother candidates. The theological studies  are spent in scholasticate presently located in Abidjan ([[Ivory Coast]]), Nairobi ([[Kenya]]), [[Merrivale, Devon|Merrivale (Devon)]], [[South Africa]] and [[Jerusalem]]. The society admits persons of all nationalities.\n\n==Dress and membership==\nThe habit of the missionaries resembles the white robes of the Algerian Arabs and consists of a [[cassock]] or [[gandoura]], and a [[Mantle (vesture)|mantle]] or [[burnous]]. A [[rosary]] and [[cross]] are worn around the neck in imitation of the [[mesbaha]] of the [[marabout]]s.\n\nThe society depends directly on the [[Congregation for the Evangelization of Peoples]]. The White Fathers succeeded in establishing small missions among the [[Kabyle people|Kabyle Berbers]], there being at present nine hundred and sixty-two Christians; but the regions bordering on the Great Lakes and Sudan show the best results. The number of [[wikt:neophyte|neophyte]]s in all the vicariates (as of June 1909) was 135,000; the number preparing for [[baptism]] 151,480. A test of four years is imposed on those desiring to be baptized. To religious instruction the missionaries add lessons in reading and writing, and teach also, in special classes, the tongue of the European nation governing the country, which was mostly French in these areas. The brothers train the young people for trades and agriculture. The number of boys in the schools (June, 1909) was 22,281.[[Image:Cypress Grove House.jpg|thumb|Cypress Grove House, home of the White Fathers in Ireland]]\n\nIn January 2006, the society numbered; 9 bishops, 1,498 priests, 156 brothers; 16 clerics with perpetual oath, and 5 associates. There were 354 students preparing to enter the society.\n\n==Leaders==\n\nUnder the leadership of Archbishop (later Cardinal) [[Charles Lavigerie|Charles-Martial Allemand-Lavigerie]], General Superiors were:<ref name=MafrGCatholic>{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Missionaries of Africa M. Afr.||}} |url=http://www.gcatholic.org/orders/030.htm\n |title=Missionaries of Africa M. Afr.|| |work=GCatholic|accessdate=2013-04-19}}</ref>\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n| 1874 || 1880|| Fr. Francisque Deguerry\n|-\n| 1880 || 1885|| Fr. [[Jean-Baptiste-Fr\u00e9zal Charbonnier]] (later Bishop)\n|-\n| 1885? || 1886|| Fr. [[L\u00e9once Bridoux]] (later Bishop)\n|-\n| 1886 || 1889|| Fr. Francisque Deguerry\n|-\n| 1889 || 1894||Bishop [[L\u00e9on Livinhac]] (later Archbishop)\n|}\n[[File:Mgr Lavigerie.jpg|thumb| Lavigerie memorial in [[Algiers]]]]\nLater Superiors General were:<ref name=MafrGCatholic/>\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n| 1894 || 1922.11.11|| Archbishop [[L\u00e9on Livinhac]]\n|-\n| 1922 || 1936|| Fr. [[Paul Voillard]]\n|-\n| 1936.04.22 || 1947.04.30|| Bishop [[Joseph-Marie Birraux]] \n|-\n| 1947.05.05 || 1957|| Bishop [[Louis-Marie-Joseph Durrieu]] \n|-\n| 1957 || 1967|| Fr. [[L\u00e9on Volker]] \n|-\n| 1967 || 1974|| Fr. [[Th\u00e9oz Van Asten]]\n|-\n| 1974 || 1980|| Fr. [[Jean-Marie Vasseur]] \n|-\n| 1980 || 1986|| Fr. [[Robert Marie Gay]] (later Bishop)\n|-\n| 1986 || 1992|| Fr. [[Etienne Renaud]]\n|-\n| 1992 || 1998|| Fr. [[Gothard Rosner]] \n|-\n| 1998 || 2004.06.02|| Fr. [[Fran\u00e7ois Richard, White Father|Fran\u00e7ois Richard]] \n|-\n| 2004.06.02 || 2010.05.31|| Fr. [[G\u00e9rard Chabanon]]\n|-\n| 2010.05.31 ||  || Fr. [[Richard Baawobr]] (became Bishop of Wa - Ghana earlier in 2016)\n|- \n| 2016.05.27 ||  || Fr. [[Stanley Lubungo]]\n|}\n\n==Zambia==\nThe White Fathers also created mission stations in what was then [[Northern Rhodesia]] (now [[Zambia]]), particularly in the [[Luwingu]] District.  \n\n'''The Catholic Church in Zambia and the Missionaries of Africa (The White Fathers)''' (from the General House of the Missionaries of Africa - White Fathers)\n\nThe first Catholic Missionaries in what is now called Zambia were the international Society of the Missionaries of Africa, popularly called 'The White Fathers\u2019 because of their white dress. They arrived from what is now called Tanzania in 1891, and established the first mission post called Mwambwe Mwela. They were hierarchically structured with Bishop Joseph Dupont firmly in charge , something that appealed to the Bemba overlords. One of the reasons that bloodshed was avoided was his reconciliation during one of their succession disputes. They settled down successfully in the North of what was then called Northern Rhodesia but did not follow those who migrated to the copper mines and the capital Lusaka during the 1930's. This practice was changed in 1965, after the Second Vatican Council, when a younger group of White Fathers responded to the national requirements of the apostolate. \nAround the beginning of the new millennium their missionary endeavour was taken over, almost entirely, by the local clergy.\n\n==See also==\n[[File:Maison g\u00e9n\u00e9ralice.jpg|thumb|right|General House in Rome]]\n* [[Catholic missions]]\n* [[Burkard Huwiler|Bishop Burkhard Huwiler]]\n* [[Joseph Dupont (bishop)|Bishop Joseph Dupont]]\n* [[Melkite Greek Catholic Church]]\n* [[Kungoni|Mua Mission, Malawi]]\n* [[Catholic youth sports associations of French Algeria]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{CathEncy|wstitle=White Fathers}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://mafrome.org/home/ International Website of the Missionaries of Africa]\n* [http://www.missionariesofafrica.org/ Missionaries of Africa UK]\n* [http://www.mafrwestafrica.net/ Missionaries of Africa in West Africa]\n\n[[Category:White Fathers| ]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1868]]\n", "name_user": "Jovin Joseph Rwetabula", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White_Fathers"}
{"title_page": "Faustino Asprilla", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name                 = Faustino Asprilla\n | image                =\n | image_size           = \n | fullname             = Faustino Hern\u00e1n Asprilla Hinestroza\n | height               = 1.76 m\n | birth_date           = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1969|11|10}}\n | birth_place          = [[Tulu\u00e1]], Colombia\n | position             = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<br/>[[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|Attacking midfielder]]\n | youthclubs1          = Sarmiento Lora\n | youthyears1          = 1986\u20131987\n | years1   = 1988\u20131989 | caps1   = 36 | goals1   = 17 | clubs1   = [[C\u00facuta Deportivo]]\n | years2   = 1989\u20131992 | caps2   = 75 | goals2   = 32 | clubs2   = [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]]\n | years3   = 1992\u20131996 | caps3   = 84 | goals3   = 25 | clubs3   = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]\n | years4   = 1996\u20131998 | caps4   = 48 | goals4   = 9  | clubs4   = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n | years5   = 1998\u20131999 | caps5   = 12 | goals5   = 1  | clubs5   = [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]\n | years6   = 1999\u20132000 | caps6   = 12 | goals6   = 2  | clubs6   = [[Sociedade Esportiva Palmeiras|Palmeiras]]\n | years7   = 2000\u20132001 | caps7   = 12 | goals7   = 8  | clubs7   = [[Fluminense FC|Fluminense]]\n | years8   = 2001\u20132002 | caps8   = 12 | goals8   = 3  | clubs8   = [[Atlante F.C.|Atlante]]\n | years9   = 2002      | caps9   = 11 | goals9   = 3  | clubs9   = [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]]\n | years10  = 2003      | caps10  = 13 | goals10  = 5  | clubs10  = [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]]\n | years11  = 2003\u20132004 | caps11  = 2  | goals11  = 0  | clubs11  = [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes La Plata]]\n | years12  = 2004      | caps12  = 1  | goals12  = 0  | clubs12  = [[Cortulu\u00e1]]\n | totalcaps = 318 | totalgoals  = 105\n | nationalyears1 = 1993\u20132001 | nationalcaps1 = 57 | nationalgoals1 = 20 | nationalteam1 = [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]]\n}}\n{{spanish name 2|Asprilla|Hinestroza}}\n'''Faustino Hern\u00e1n''' \"'''Tino'''\" '''Asprilla Hinestroza''' (born 10 November 1969) is a Colombian former professional [[association football|footballer]] who most notably played for [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]], [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]] as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. Though never a prolific goalscorer, he was a quick, agile and skilful player known for his flair, creativity, power and pace, as well as his ability to create chances and score spectacular goals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnstar.com/editorial/news/detail/item704033/Asprilla's-magical-European-night|title=Asprilla's magical European night|publisher=ESPN|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130122074530/http://www.espnstar.com/editorial/news/detail/item704033/Asprilla's-magical-European-night/|archive-date=22 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1994-06-15/features/9406150766_1_baggio-great-soccer-players-goals-in-world|title=Baggio Takes Great Strides Toward Soccer Greatness|newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel|author1=Mike Zizzo|date=15 June 1994|accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref> In 1993, he was named by [[FIFA]] as the [[1993 FIFA World Player of the Year|sixth-best player in the world]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1029888/Newcastle-legend-Asprilla-arrested-peppering-defence-shots--using-machine-gun.html |title=Newcastle legend Asprilla arrested after peppering the defence with shots - using a machine gun|accessdate=6 February 2011|newspaper=Mail Online| location=London| date=27 June 2008}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}}\n\nDespite his talent, he was known for being temperamental and controversial both on and off the field.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://fourfourtwo.com/news/southamerica/78575/default.aspx|title=Falcao form boosts troubled Colombia|magazine=FourFourTwo|date=29 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.footballfancast.com/2009/12/football-blogs/happened-faustino-asprilla|title=Whatever happened to Newcastle\u2019s Faustino Asprilla?|publisher=FootballFanCast|date=31 December 2009}}</ref> He was also known for his somersault then double-fist-pump [[goal celebration]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Power Ranking the Best Newcastle Strikers of the Past 20 Years |url=https://2bleacherreport.com/articles/1743666-power-ranking-the-best-newcastle-strikers-of-the-past-20-years#slide0 |accessdate=15 October 2018 |agency=Bleacher Report}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Early years===\nAfter starting out playing football with local team Carlos Sarmiento Lora School, Asprilla started his professional career in 1988 for the Colombian team [[C\u00facuta Deportivo]] at the age of 18 for a year before transferring to [[Atl\u00e9tico Nacional]]. Thirty-five goals in seventy-eight games brought him to the attention to several Italian clubs who bid for him, with [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] winning the race to sign him for US$10.9 million in 1992.\n\n===Parma===\nIn [[1992\u201393 Serie A|his first season at Parma]], Asprilla scored some important goals, including a 27-yard second-half free-kick which helped Parma defeat [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] 1\u20130, ending [[1991\u201392 Serie A|the Italian champions']] unbeaten streak at 58 matches.<ref name=\"ESPN\">{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/story/_/id/1031419/the-mavericks:-faustino-asprilla?cc=3436|title=The Mavericks: Faustino Asprilla|publisher=ESPN Soccernet|date=8 March 2012}}</ref> It was at Parma Asprilla arguably enjoyed his greatest club success. Asprilla was part of the Parma squad which won its first international tournament, the [[1992\u201393 European Cup Winners' Cup]], scoring four goals in eight matches. It was his brace in Spain that rallied the Italian team to a 2\u20131 victory over [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] in the semi-final. However, an injury meant he was an unused substitute as Parma defeated Belgian club [[Royal Antwerp F.C.|Royal Antwerp]] 3\u20131 in [[1993 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|the final]].<ref name=\"ESPN\" />\n\nIn early 1994, Asprilla was part of the Parma side which defeated Milan 0\u20132 at the [[San Siro]] to overturn a 0\u20131 first leg deficit and claim the [[1993 European Super Cup]].\n\nAlso in [[1993\u201394 Serie A|the 1993\u201394 season]], Parma reached a second [[1993\u201394 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] [[1994 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|final]]. However, a 0\u20131 defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] meant they would not retain their trophy.\n\nIn [[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994\u201395]], Parma again reached the final of a major European competition as they faced Italian compatriots [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in the [[1995 UEFA Cup Final|final]] of the [[1994\u201395 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]. Asprilla was instrumental in Parma's run to the final, with three goals over two legs in the semi-final against [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-italy-2-germany-0-1616278.html|title=Italy 2 Germany 0|newspaper=The Independent|date=19 April 1995}}</ref> In the final itself, Asprilla was in the starting XI for both legs as Parma defeated Juventus 2\u20131 on aggregate.\n\nAt the start of the [[1995\u201396 Serie A|1995\u201396 season]], Asprilla found himself out of head coach [[Nevio Scala]]'s plans. In February 1996, after making only six appearances in the opening five months of the season,<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/newcastle-demands-block-asprilla-move-1317334.html|title=Newcastle demands block Asprilla move|newspaper=The Independent|date=5 February 1996}}</ref> Asprilla joined English [[Premier League]] leaders [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] for a \u00a36.7&nbsp;million transfer fee.\n\nDuring his first spell at Parma, Asprilla scored 25 goals in 84 [[Serie A]] appearances.<ref name=\"independent\" /> He is considered one of the greatest players of [[History of Parma F.C.#Serie A and Scala's success (1990\u20131994)|Parma's successful period in the 1990s]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/837116-parma-parmas-15-greatest-players-of-the-parmalat-era/page/2|title=Parma: 15 Greatest Players of the Parmalat Era|publisher=The Blecher Report}}</ref> In his three full seasons with the club, Parma finished [[1992\u201393 Parma A.C. season|third]], [[1993\u201394 Parma A.C. season|fifth]] and [[1994\u201395 Parma A.C. season|third]] in Serie A. The club also reached a European final in each of those seasons, as well as the [[1994\u201395 Coppa Italia]] final.\n\n*[[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup]] winner: [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1992\u201393|1992/93]]\n*UEFA Cup Winners' Cup runner-up: [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1993\u201394|1993/94]]\n*[[European Super Cup]] winner: 1993\n*[[UEFA Cup]] winner: [[UEFA Cup 1994\u201395|1994/95]], [[UEFA Cup 1998\u201399|1998/99]]\n\n===Newcastle United===\nParma sold Asprilla to English Premier League side Newcastle United for \u00a36.7&nbsp;million in February 1996, with \"Tino\", as the fans nicknamed him, appearing at [[St James' Park]] to finalise the move during a snowstorm, dressed in a fur coat. At the time, Newcastle were ahead of [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in the [[1995\u201396 FA Premier League|Premier League]], although their lead at the top of the table was narrowing. Asprilla's arrival on [[Tyneside]] came just months after earlier media reports of a move to England, with [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] being linked with his signature.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/that-was-the-season-that-was-1345862.html]</ref>\n\nAsprilla made his league debut in Newcastle's 2\u20131 win over [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] at the [[Riverside Stadium]], coming on as a second-half substitute with the score 1\u20130 in Middlesbrough's favour. He made an immediate impact, creating the assist for Newcastle's equaliser. However, his time on Tyneside was blighted by inconsistency and off-field incidents, and Asprilla was blamed as one of the reasons Newcastle would go on to concede the 1995\u201396 Premier League title to eventual winners Manchester United.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nAsprilla's second season for Newcastle ended with the club finishing in second place once again, behind Manchester United. His role was largely reduced to substitute appearances, although he retained his best performances for the club's [[1996\u201397 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] campaign, scoring five goals. His celebration of the goal he scored against [[FC Metz|Metz]], whereby he removed his shirt and swung it from a corner flag, resulted in Asprilla being given a yellow card, meaning a suspension from Newcastle's next UEFA Cup match against [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]].\n\nThe 1997\u201398 season was Asprilla's last for Newcastle. With the sale of striker [[Les Ferdinand]] to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and a serious injury to [[Alan Shearer]] during the pre-season, Asprilla was preferred as first choice striker alongside the young, inexperienced [[Jon Dahl Tomasson]]. With the club competing in that season's [[1997\u201398 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], Asprilla [[List of UEFA Champions League hat-tricks|scored a hat-trick]] for Newcastle in a 3\u20132 win over [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], which would be his last goals for the club.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DPGe9OrT53Y \u2013 Highlight of the Newcastle 3\u20132 victory against Barcelona]</ref> By the end of January 1998, with Newcastle struggling in the league and eliminated from the Champions League, Asprilla's time at Newcastle came to an end. He was sold back to Parma for \u00a36&nbsp;million, having scored a total of 9 goals in 48 Premier League appearances and 9 goals in 11 European matches.\n\n===Return to Parma===\nIn his second spell at Parma, Asprilla won his second UEFA Cup, coming on as a substitute as Parma defeated [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] in the [[1999 UEFA Cup Final|final]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-parma-seize-blancs-gift-1093340.html\n|title=Football: Parma seize Blanc's gift\n|newspaper=The Independent\n|date=12 May 1999 |accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Palmeiras===\nAsprilla played in the successful Palmeiras team in the 1999 and 2000 seasons.\n\n*[[Torneio Rio-S\u00e3o Paulo|Rio-S\u00e3o Paulo Tournament]] winner: 2000\n*[[Copa dos Campe\u00f5es|Brazilian Champions Cup]] winner: 2000\n\n===Later career and Darlington link===\nAlthough his brief time with Palmeiras saw the team achieve success, for Asprilla personally his time there marked the beginning of a pattern of short, relatively unproductive stays with various clubs across various countries, including Brazil, Mexico, Chile, Colombia and Argentina.\n\nDuring a time which was generally low-key, he appeared in the public eye again in 2002 amid reports he had been approached by English [[Football League Third Division|Division Three]] side [[Darlington F.C.|Darlington]]. Darlington successfully appealed an initial work permit refusal and had offered around \u00a317,000 per week plus 20% of gate receipts, a car and a rent-free flat. Chairman [[George Reynolds (business)|George Reynolds]] considered they were friends and in fact paraded Asprilla in front of 5,163 fans before Darlington's 2-0 win over [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] on 27 August, believing the intended two-year contract was good as signed. However, it was reported that after Asprilla stalled on taking a medical on 29 August, in the early hours of 30 August, Asprilla caught a flight from Newcastle Airport to the Middle East, apparently to accept a more lucrative contract offer. Reynolds described himself as \"absolutely gutted\" by the snub, complaining Asprilla \"did not even have the decency to say goodbye\" and said he would never talk to him again.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/d/darlington/2222014.stm|title=Asprilla snubs Darlington|accessdate=6 February 2011|work=BBC Sport|date=30 August 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/darlington-left-furious-as-asprilla-flies-away-641529.html|title=Darlington left furious as Asprilla flies away|work=The Independent|date=31 August 2002 | location=London | first=Jim | last=Van Wijk}}</ref> This was the second time Darlington was snubbed by a high-profile ex-Newcastle player that summer, the first being [[Paul Gascoigne]].\n\nThe identity of the Middle East club has never been revealed and whether Asprilla did join them remains a mystery.\n\nThere is no official record of Asprilla playing for another professional team after his departure from Argentine side [[Estudiantes de La Plata]] in 2004.\n\n==International career==\n===Summary===\nAsprilla scored 20 goals in 57 matches for [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] from 1993 to 2001 and played for his country at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]] and [[1998 FIFA World Cup]]s. Asprilla was expected to be one of the top players of the 1994 tournament, but failed to score a single goal as Colombia was eliminated in the first round.\n\n===1992 Summer Olympics===\nAsprilla was a member of the Colombian team at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] in [[Barcelona]] where the team was eliminated in the first round following losses to Spain (4\u20130) and Egypt (3\u20134) and a draw with Qatar (1\u20131).\n\n===1993 Copa America===\nIn the [[1993 Copa Am\u00e9rica]], held in Ecuador, Colombia finished third overall. After topping Group C with a 2\u20131 win over [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] and draws with [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] (1\u20131) and [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] (1\u20131), Colombia defeated [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] 1\u20131 (5\u20133 on penalties) before losing 0\u20130 (6\u20135 on penalties) to Argentina in the semi-final, the eventual tournament winners. In the match for third place, Colombia defeated hosts [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] 1\u20130 to claim third place. Asprilla did not score in the tournament.\n\n===1994 FIFA World Cup===\nAsprilla was part of the Colombian team which demolished Argentina 5\u20130 in a World Cup Qualifier match in [[Buenos Aires]] in 1993, where Asprilla scored twice. Colombia finished undefeated in the South American qualifying group. Entering the 1994 World Cup, there were high expectations for Colombia as a dark horse favourite to win the tournament with a squad that included such notable players as [[Carlos Valderrama]], [[Freddy Rinc\u00f3n]] and Asprilla. However, with one win and two losses, Colombia finished at the bottom of their group and was eliminated after the first round. Asprilla himself had a disappointing tournament, failing to score, and even walked out on his teammates midway through the group stage.\n\n===1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica===\nIn the [[1995 Copa Am\u00e9rica]], held and won by Uruguay, Colombia again finished third. Colombia started out by finishing third in Group B with a 1\u20131 draw with [[Peru national football team|Peru]] (Asprilla scored the goal), a 1\u20130 win over Ecuador and a 0\u20133 loss to [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]. The nation then went on to defeat [[Paraguay national football team|Paraguay]] 5\u20134 on penalties after a 1\u20131 draw in the quarter-finals before losing to Uruguay 2\u20130 in the semi-final. In the third place match, Colombia faced the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]], which Colombia easily defeated 4\u20131 with Asprilla scoring one of the Colombians' four goals in the match.\n\n===1998 FIFA World Cup===\nIn the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], held in France, expectations were again high for Colombia and Asprilla remained in the team. However, again Colombia was eliminated in the first round following one win and two losses. Asprilla was dismissed from the team after complaining to reporters about the head coach's decision to substitute him near the end of Colombia's opening loss against [[Romania national football team|Romania]].\n\nIn 2001, at age 32, Asprilla retired from international football.\n\n==Retirement==\nIn July 2009, Asprilla officially retired from top flight football following a retirement match in Medell\u00edn, Colombia. Although this marks his official retirement date, he had not been actively employed by a professional side in around five years.\n\nIn 2008, he was arrested for allegedly firing a machine gun at security forces near his farm in Colombia. He was placed under house arrest on charges of weapons possession and criminal damage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1029888/Newcastle-legend-Asprilla-arrested-peppering-defence-shots--using-machine-gun.html |title=Newcastle legend Asprilla arrested after peppering the defence with shots - using a machine gun|accessdate=6 February 2011|newspaper=Mail Online| location=London| author=Sportsmail Reporter| date=27 June 2008}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=November 2019}} He has appeared in various Colombian Reality Shows, such as ''Desafio'' 2005 and ''Nomadas''.\n\nHe made a return to St James' Park on 22 January 2011 appearing on the pitch at half time during Newcastle United's Premier League home match against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] and attended a charity dinner in [[Gateshead]] that evening, alongside Les Ferdinand and [[Peter Beardsley]], where he spoke of his affection for the Newcastle fans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/north-east-news/evening-chronicle-news/2011/01/22/faustino-asprilla-entertains-at-charity-event-72703-28035497/|title=Faustino Asprilla entertains at charity event|publisher=ChronicleLive, the Evening Chronicle newspaper online|date=22 January 2011 | location=North East | first=James | last=Moore}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2013, Asprilla was linked with a return to his former club Newcastle. Asprilla spoke of performing a coaching role with the youth squad as well as developing a special role in introducing young talent into the academy from his homeland Colombia. His intention is to give Colombians a chance to showcase their skills in European/English football, based on the sheer amount of talent that has come from Colombia in recent years.\n\nAsprilla played in former ''Magpies'' goalkeeper [[Steve Harper]]'s testimonial match on 11 September 2013 against [[A.C. Milan|A.C. Milan Glorie]]. He had a header disallowed for offside before the Italians won 2\u20131 on penalties.<ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/steve-harper-testimonial-newcastle-milan-2267895</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, it was revealed Asprilla was preparing to launch a range of flavoured condoms in Colombia.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/sep/25/faustino-asprilla-launch-line-condoms-colombia-guava-flavour</ref>\n\nAsprilla revealed in 2019 that a hitman wanted to murder Paraguay goalkeeper [[Jose Luis Chilavert]] after both were sent off during a [[1998 FIFA World Cup]] qualifier.<ref>https://www.thedailyawaaz.com/news/sports/839</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n:Sources:<ref>{{NFT|12577|name=Faustino Asprilla|accessdate= }}</ref><ref>http://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/faustino-asprilla/2/</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division||Apps||Goals||Apps||Go